    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Stuckenia pectinata</i> is statewide, while other <i>Stuckenia</i> and <i>Potamogeton</i> species are distributed regionally.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ad, Ah, Ak). Stands of <i>S. pectinata</i> from Suisun Marsh (Baye et al. 2000, Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000) and the Sacramento- San Joaquin River delta (Hickson and Keeler-Wolf 2007) occur in flooded marshes or in open channels adjacent to in-streams. Stands of <i>S. filiformis, S. pectinata,</i> and <i>Potamogeton zosteriformis</i> occur at the San Francisco Bay estuary (Holstein 2000).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Al-m, Ar). Stands occur in brackish to freshwater sloughs in the delta region of the section (Hickson and Keeler-Wolf 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ae). Stands from Humboldt Bay National Wildlife Refuge (Pickart 2006) are local in managed wetlands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Eg, Em, Ep-q). Stands occurring sporadically in lakes, including stands in Yosemite National Park, have <i>P. epihydrus, P. gramineus,</i> and <i>P. natans</i> as dominants (CVIS 2007). Other stands have been observed south of the park.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bh). A stand of <i>S. pectinata</i> occurs in a small reservoir on the east side of San Clemente Island (Junak et al. 2007).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Stuckenia pectinata </i>provides forage for ducks and other waterfowl; plants are encouraged to grow in some managed wildlife areas. </div>
</div>

    

    

